{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580370/1946060701/0219.xml":{"full_text":"Pa ere Four ____\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nOfficial Publication\nToledo Industrial Lnion Council\nORGAMZE TOLEDO 100%\nPublished every Friday by Local No 11\nUAW-CIO. 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nMember of American Labor Press Association\nFditnr ________Melvin Schult*\nMaXing M\u00abor -------------r0^\nMember American Newspaper Gutld-C/O\nAdvertising Manager .\u201eBurny Zawodny\nBoard of Trustees\nMelvin Schultz. Thomas Burke,\nRandolph Gray\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne rear, by mail, in advance\u2014$1.50\nEntered at the Toledo, Ohio, post office as\nsecond class matter under the act or\nAug. 24, 1912\nAn Old Fallacy\nin pointing out that increased com\nmodify prices have almost completely\nwiped out recent wage raises, Richard\nGosser, UAW-CIO director, placed his\nfinger accurately upon an old fallacy re\ngarding wages.\nThere can he no doubt that the OPA,\nbig business, newspapers and the forces\nwhich form public opinion, have to a con\nsiderable extent succeeded in convincing a\nlarge part of the public that the higher\nprices of commodities are due to the\nhigher wages granted to labor.\nDirector Gosser in pointing out that\nwage increases always follow price ad\nvances was making an observation that\nevery worker in this country should know.\nIt was true during the war and it is true\ntoday, that the wages of the workers never\ndid balance with the price structure and\nthat only by long hours of overtime dur\ning the war w'ere the wage earners able to\nkeep up with increasing prices.\nOPA, big business and the newspapers\nhave sought to make it appear that the\nprice hikes have been due to increased\nwages, when it is obvious that exactly the\nopposite is the truth. Thus, when the dis\nparity between wages and prices reaches\nthe point where the workers cannot earn\na fair living, more wage demands are made\nand eventually won and more price hikes\ncome about, again on the grounds that in\ncreased labor costs force the increases in\nprices.\nThrough this upward spiral comes an\ninflationary process, which, if not con\ntrolled by government eventually leads\nto a breakdown in the economic chain\nwith a resultant downward spiral in which\nwages decrease first to be followed by\nprices. The upward spiral is completely\nreversed and the wage earner^, it they are\nfortunate enough to hav$ juos, find them\nselves again handicapped in a deflationary\nprocess which leads to economic stagna\ntion, and aa was the case in the last de\npression, to near-chaos.\nWhile millions of dollarrin increased\nwages have ben granted to the Auto Work\ners in Northwestern Ohio, the value of the\ninflated dollar becomes meaningless in the\nface of advances in all prices which con\nspires to rob the worker of his gains and\nplaces him in the same position in which\nhe found himself, following V-J Day when\nhe suffered a 30 per cent loss in pay due\nto reduction of working hours.\nIn the face of the inflationary process\nwhich is taking place, and we are told that\nthis is only the beginning, there can be no\nalternative for the workers except to seek\nadd itional wages.\nWe all know what has oceured in the\npast few months as a result of labor's de\nmand for justifiable and necessary wage\nincreases. Strikes, industrial warfare, anti\nlabor legislation, governmental strike\nbreaking and a bitter struggle in which\nlabor hag been victimized by\na hostile\npress, a stupid administration, reactionary\nlegislators and hig business\u2019 have robbed\nthe workers of their just demands and\nturned a large section of public opinion\nagainst all labor.\nTo combat the forces which have been\nat work, and to a large extent succeeded\nin discrediting labor, it is necessary that\nthe unions of the country unite themselves\nin common cause against their common\nenemy. They must begin now, before it is\ntoo late to effectively combat the forces\nwhich have not only deprived them of\ntheir just wages, but which have sought\nand succeeded in making the American\npeople believe the lie that prices follow\nwage*.\nI charge that the motives (of the real re\nfate lobby) are to perpetuate the housing\nshortage in order to continue to gain specula\ntive profits at the expense of veterans.\u2019\u2019\n\"'flson Wyatt, Housing Expediter.\nDog foods and platinum were freed from\nprice ceilings recently and platinum prices\nimmediately jumped $21 an ounce. Incidental\nly, have you tried to buy anything for a dime\nla a dune \u00abtor\u00ab recently?\nSpeaking of the revised Full Employment\nbill. Senator Robert A. Taft said recently:\n\u201cThe full employment* is eliminated, the \u2019na\ntional reassertion of the right to work\u2019 is eli\nminated, and the bill does not bear any re\nsemblance to the bill which was orginally in\ntroduced. I do not think that any Republican\nneed fear voting for the bill.\u2019\u2019\nThe Natl. Federation of Telephone Work\ners, which will hold its 12th annual conven\ntion starting June 2. may be starting a revolu\ntion that will break the hearts of many old\ntime union orators. Its proposed new eon\nsitution provides that \u201cNo nominating speech\nmay exceed two minutes in length.\u201d It wasn\u2019t\nmany years ago, old-timers recall, that a can\ndidate for union office was looked on with\nthe deepest suspicion if his nominating speech\ndidn\u2019t last more than three hourt.\nPolitical\nAction\nby\nClayton\nRusch\nChairman\nof the\nrs*l-4\nPolitical Action Committee I\nOne of the principles upon\nwhich this nation was founded\nis the proposition that \u201cGov\nernments derive their just\npowers from the consent of\nthe governed.\u201d In other words\nthe government derives its au\nthority from the people. It\nfollows from this that the\ngovernment has an obligation\nand\na\nresponsibility to the\npeople.\nIn attempting to tackle the\nlabor problem and take steps\nto prevent industrial strife,\nthe government is only ful\nfilling its responsibility.\nIn attempting to superfi\ncially remove effects in an\narbitrary manner and doing\nnothing to remove the causes\nof strikes, the government is\nfailing in its responsibility.\nWhen Congress and the ad\nministration attempt to solve\nthe very rights which labor\nhas won only after years of\nhard and bitter struggle it\nfails completely to understand\neither the problem or its cor\nrect solution\nOrganized labor as a whole\ndoes not seek or desire strikes.\nThe strike weapon is used\nonly as a last resort. For ex\nample, no strike can be *9iled\nin the UAW-CIO except with\nthe authorization of the Inter\nnational executive board.\nPRINCIPLES\nPIO unions have four guid\ning principles which must be\ncomplied with before a strike\nis called. These are:\n(1) Conditions must be In\ntolerable\n(2) Other means of settling\nthe dispute must be exhaust\ned.\n(3) The harm which will\naccrue to others as a result of\nthe strike must be less than\nthe gain sought by the union.\n(4) The strike must have\nsome chance of success.\nThe government definitely\nhas a responsibility to attempt\nto prevent strikes from taking\nplace. This responsibility can\nbe fulfilled in the best inter\nests of fall the people if ways\nare employed to remove the\ncauses of strikes. This means\nan Improved conciliation serv\nice. It means pressure must\nbe applied on certain recalci\ntrant employers who refuse to\nbargain in good faith with the\nUnion who represent* their\nemployees.\nTo attempt to solve the\nproblem by curbing the right\nto strike is class legislation of\nthe most brazen sort. It is\nnothing more or less than an\nattack upon one of the most\nbasic rights of the people.\nLEGISLATION\nAND CONCILIATION\nLegislation to compel fac\ntory owners to operate their\nnlants, whether or not they\nmade a profit, would be no\nmore ridiculous than legisla\ntion to compel employees to\nstay on the job whether or not\ntliev earn living wages.\nWhat we actually need is\nlegislation to guarantee a min\nimum annual wage. In the\nmeantime the workers must\nuse their economic power to\ncompel their employers to pay\na living wage. This means the\nright to strike cannot be\ncurbed unless we are ready to\nabandon the whole idea of a\nnation of free men and women.\nAlthough anti labor legisla\ntion directly affects the wel\nfare of those who labor, and\nthis group is indisputedly a\nmajority, the welfare of the\nfarm, small business, and pro\nfessional groups will be ad\nversely affected by such im\npractical attempts to solve the\nlabor problem.\nEveryone of us should sit\ndown right now and write to\nthe President, also Senators\nJames Huffman and Robert\nTaft and to Representatives\nHomer Ramey and George\nBender, Washington, D. C. on\nthis issue.\nWe must Inform our elected\nrepresentatives that improved\nconciliation service and better\ncompensation laws will great\nly help matters and that pass\nage of anti-labor legislation\nwill only shake the very foun\ndations of this nation which is\n\u201cdedicated to the proposition\nthat all men are created\nequal.**\nIt\u2019s News\nTo Me...\nBy O. J. Pecord\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nLooking at the labor movement in America today, we find\nthat it is completely divided because of the jurisdictional na\nture of the unions involved.\nWe discover that both the CIO and AFL are organizing the\nSouth and that the struggle not only involves fighting the re\nactionary industrialists below the Mason and Dixon line, but in\nfighting each other to prove to the workers that each is the\nbest union.\nJohn L. Lewis for organizational reasons has taken his\nUnited Mine Workers back into the AFL, while the Interna\ntional Machinists, because of a jurisdictional dispute in the\nAFL, took their union out and became independent.\nUNIONS AND UNIONS ANNOYING\nIn the railroad industry we discover that there are 20\ntmions involved and that many are working at cross purposes.\nSo disastrous is the division among the rail unions that Presi\ndent Truman was able to break the Brotherhoods strike with a\nthreat, secure in the knowledge that the only ones who could\nand would break the strike were the railroad unions them\nselves.\nWhat worked in the railroad strike will not and did not\nwork in the coal miners\u2019 strike, because the miners, while com\nposed of different crafts, are united in a strong industrial\nunion. The only ones who could break the coal strike were the\nminers. Realizing this, the coal miners were able to ignore\ngovernment seizure and win their points.\nIndependent unions, such as the MESA and others, some\nyears ago formed a confederation of independent unions for th?\npurpose of uniting their forces for joint economic and political\npurposes. Today, the confederation has fallen apart with each\nunion going its separate way.\nAnd in the face of all this division in the ranks of labor,\nwe are asked to believe that the unions of this country, uniting\nthemselves with the farmers, can succeed in bringing about\npolitical unity and an effective political party.\nSuch a contention, while it is idealistic, is definitely not\nrealistic in the face of the very apparent fact that labor cannot\nsucceed in uniting even in its most important consideraion, its\ncommon economic interest.\nEDUCATION NEEDED\nWhat is needed and what some unions are making a sin\ncere endeavor to give their members is political education\nwhich is the only possible answer to the problem of labor s\npolitical disunity.\nOne of the outstanding jobs ever done by any union is that\nwhich has been initiated and continued by the CIO\u2019s Poiltical\nAction Committee. The fact that some CIO leaders are clamor\ning for united labor political action is living proof that the\neducation campaign is beginning to work, for those who study\nthe political situation as it affects labor cannot help but even\ntually reach the point where they realize that independent po\nliical action in futile unless all of labor is united behind the\nmovement.\nAs a matter of fact, there will never be any successful\nindependent political action by labor until labor itself becomes\nunited. Since this is obviously far away at the present time, it\nmust of necessity follow that independent political action will\nnot and cannot succeed when labor unions are still in process\nof organizing the unorganized and consolidating their gains.\nTHERE IIS HOPE\nNor is jhe answer to the problem of labor in the political\nfield to be found in some mixbreed type of political organiza\ntion. for it is not human nature to check its other interests at\nthe door as it enters upon a program with other unions and the\nsame divisions which now exist in labor organizations would\nbe carried over into the political field.\nDespite the many obstacles which impede the organiza\ntion, progress and success of independent labor political action,\nthere is still hope. There are always groups of reactionaries in\nCongress and every state legislature who by their reactionary\nmeasures force labor to unite from time to time in its common\ninterest, These are the people who will eventually manage to\npull the major error which will actually wipe out jurisdictional\nlines sufficiently to drive the workers into the type of unity\nthat must prevail before political sucess is possible.\nIn the meantime, a vast educational program for the work\ners must be undertaken by all labor unions to acquaint their\nmembers with the fact that their economic interests and po\nliical interests are not separate and distinct things, but one and\ninseparable. If any considerable number of Americans ever\nreach that point, and it will probably be a long time before\nthey do, we WiU not need worry about independent political\naction for labor. It will come as surely as night follows day,\nand nothing, not even labor leaders themselves will be able to\nprevent it.\nWhile we are waiting for the labor movement to reach\npolitical unity, we should do our part by joining PAC and con\ntribute our bit to our own and the political education of our\nfellow workers both in and out of CIO.\n\u2019\u2018\u2022/A\n\u2022rH by don't they }u*l phone?\"\n.News from Washington brings information that a lot of labor\nleaders are completely fed up with both the Democrats and\nRepublicans and are toying with the thought, of launching a\nthird party to be composed of labor, farmers and all who are\nin sympathy with the objectives which such a party would have.\nIt is the opinion of most progressive labor leaders and\nsocial thinkers that the labor movement in this country is not\ngoing to go very far politically until it has its own political\nparty, and there is a lot of merit and truth in the idea, but the\nideal and reality are far apart and labor cannot afford to let\nits wishbone run away with its sense of reality.\nV*\n.fest\n.V\nk\ni..'\nFrom The Militant\nOn\nPrejudice\nby Ruth Taylor\nDo you know the story of\nthe Southern judge who said\nhe could always tell the way\na jury would vote provided he\nknew where lay the prepon\nderance of prejudice.\nHe knew his people. Too\nOften we make up our minds\nnot according to the facts,\neven as we know them, but ac\ncording to our prejudices, our\ninstinctive likes and dislikes.\nI once knew a man who\nalways used to say\u2014generally\nin the midst of my most hectic\nargument\u2014that a woman\u2019s in\ntuitions were usually her sus\npicions. I resented that. Na\nturally. But I have to admit\nthat, if the wording is changed\nto \u201cintuitions are usually sus\npicions\" the fact is correct.\nWe just don\u2019t use our heads\nafter we get to arguing. We\ntalk in generalities, rather\nthan on specific cases. We say\nit is because to be specific is\nto be rude. It isn\u2019t. If you see\nsomething of which you dis\napprove done by an individ\nual, say so but keep it to the\nindividual and don\u2019t damn the\ngroup from which he comes as\nwell. Don\u2019t lump people into\none category. You wouldn\u2019t\nlike it yourself.\nDoesn\u2019t it annoy yeti when\nanyone picks out one labor\nman, and says all labor men\nare crooks because this or\nthat one isn\u2019t a plaster saint?\nYou instinctively come to his\ndefense, in order to defend\nyour group. (And you usually\nmake matters worse by so do\ning because you make up in\nheat what you lack in facts.)\nAnd yet\u2014don\u2019t you often do\nthe same thing?\nDon let us be swayed by\nour prejudices. Let us keep\nour own thoughts clear and\nabove such represensible prac\ntices. And let\u2019s not coin\nphrases. It isn\u2019t any better\nthan coining money\u2014and usu\nally the product is just as\nfalse.\nOrganized Labor has suf\nfered too much from prejudice\nthroughout the years for its\nmembers to ever be guilty of\nthis error. Now when, in the\nheat of conflict, there is tens\nity of feeling let us be espe\ncially careful in this regard.\nWe must keep cool, stick to\nfacts and not allow prejudice\n\u2014which in reality is lack of\nknowledge\u2014-to rear its ugly\nhead among us.\nSquibs\nBy LOREN NOBMAN\nT\u00bb II\nMore and more labor is\nfinding itself on a treadmill\ntoday\u2019s gains are wiped out in\ntomorrow\u2019s price increases.\nWe must adopt some plan of\nfighting the thing at hoth\nends. z\nWhat Lies Ahead?\nA Chicago Sun writer, Wil\nlard Shelton, says it might be\na good thing if Congress would\npass the drastic labor curbs\nsome of its loudmouthed mem\nbers have been ranting about.\nIt might prove, he sa^s, that\nantilabor legislation won't\nwork if it merely seeks to\ndoctor the boil instead of the\nbloodstream and it might\nbring labor together to fight\nits common enemies.\nAemtlly th? strikes are not\nthe cause of the trouble. They\nare the result of the trouble.\nThey are the ripples on the\nsurface signifying greater up\nheavals below. We may vet\ncome to realize that what was\nhappening in the spring and\nsummer of 1946 was part of a\ngreat revolution in mans\nways of \u201cthinking, in his habits\nor production and distribu\ntion. in his method of control\nling the great forces that dom\ninated the economic life of\nthe world for two centuries.\nGambling\nWith\nHealth\nBy BEN DOR\nHow much health do you\nwant?\nCongress is now deciding\nhow healthy the American\npeople shall be. The answer\nthat Congress comes out with\nwill depend a lot on your\nanswer to my question. How\nmuch health do you want?\nHow many babies do you\nwant to die each year? How\nmany mothers do you want\nus to lose? How many chil\ndren do you want crippled and\nkilled by the disease of child\nhood? How many cases of TB\nand cancer shall we let go un\ncaught until it is too late to\nstop their dirty work!\nI remember a teacher I had\nonce. He was an expert on\nfire control, but he also knew\na lot about health. He said\nover and over to us during the\nclass, \u201cPublic health is pur\nchasable.\u201d You can\u2019t keep\npeople alive forever, but you\ncan ransom a lot of them from\nthe diseases that kill and\ncripple millions of us each\nyear.\u201d\nIt\u2019s up to Congress\u2014and\nyou. How much health do\nyou want?\nDEMOCRATIC RIGHTS\nThree years ago, there was\nintroduced into Congress the\nWagner-Murray-Dingell Bill.\nMaybe you recognize the\nnames of the sponsors. They\nhave a long record of writing\nand supporting laws to take\ncare of the basic needs of the\npeople. But they also know\nhow to protect youg demo\ncratic rights while taking care\nof those needs.\nThe bill they Introduced\nwould provide the money and\nthe Federal supervision for\ngood program of hospitals and\nclinics, medical care, and the\ntraining of doctors and nurses.\nBut it would also protect your\nright to choose your own doc\ntor, or to join some voluntary\nhealth service plan if you\nwanted to.\nSince it was introduced the\nbill has kicked around in\nCongress getting nowhere.\nWhy? Is it because this\ncountry can\u2019t afford to spend\nthe money?\nA country that can turn out\n$200 billions worth of stuff a\nyear can afford to put a small\npart of that into keeping it\nself healthy, and taking care\nof itself when it does get sick.\nA country that has millions\nof people out of work would\nbe smart to put some of them\nto work building hospitals and\ncuring (We sick. But most im\nportant of all, we\u2019re already\nspending the money this pro\ngram, would need but we\naren't getting the services\nthat this bill would git us.\nUNFIT\nForty percent of the boys\nexamined for military service\nwere found unfit for duty. At\nleast 1/6 of them had minor\ndefects that could have been\nremedied. Many more of\nthem had ether troubles that\nmedical care could have pre\nvented. But the boys and the\ncare just didn\u2019t get together.\nMaybe the bill was never\ntaken up because we\u2019re so far\nahead of the rest of the world\nthat we have no right to any\nmore medical service. After\nall we\u2019re the richest, most\nmodern country in the world.\nDo we lead in health, too?\nNot so\u2019s you could notice it.\nThen why did the bill roll\naround for three years without\nhearing?\nBecause people like Taft of\nOhio can\u2019t see past the dollar\nsign. Perhaps they\u2019d rather\nsee people live insecurely and\ndi* prematurely than spend\nthe dollars that health and\nsecurity might cost, and agree\nthat the worker has the right te\nproper medical care. Becausf\nsome high priced doctor* lik*\nthings the way they are, an}\nwill spend the money to con*\nvince millions of other peoplg\nto leave bad enough alone. Be\ncause so many Congressmew\nspend their time looking for\npeople to hate instead of for\nchildren 'who can be kept\nstraight and strong, for middle\naged people uho can be kept\nalive and well, for older\npeople who can be kept com\nfoitable during the last year*\ntheir lives.\nYour labor organization it\nworking for the bill. Philip\nMurray and William Green\njoined with other like-minded\ncitizens in sponsoring the\nCommittee for the Nation\u2019!\nHealth (402\u20146th St. N. W.,\nWashington, D. C.) to help get\nthe bill passed. But your\nunion and the Committee need\nyour help too.\nThink of the kids who need\nyour help. Think of the\nmothers or the old folks\u2014or\nyour own tches and pains.\nPick out your own symbol of\nwhy you want this nation to\nbe healthy and well. And thea\n\u2014get into the fight for that\nsymbol.\nRegional\nViews\nBy Richard Qosser\nFriday, June 7,194$\nUATT-CIO\nDirector Region 2B,\nOur economic system from its very begin\nning has experienced a series of peaks and de-,\npressions where we go from busin ass boorr.j\nand high production to unemployment and alf\nthat joblessness means to those who must\nwork for their livings.\nWe of the labor movement do not subscribe\nto the belief that such extremes of employ\nment and unemployment are necessary. As an\naid to maintaining purchasing power we have\nsuggested, and in some small ways succeeded,\nin obtaining part of what we believe to be a\npartial remedy for periodic depressions.\nUnemployment compensation and pensions,\nwhile, they have aided in some mays in over\ncoming the worst phases of unemployment, are\ndefinitely not the complete answer to our\nproblem. They are but part .of the answer.\nThe real answer is the annual guaranteed\nwage.\nLEGISLATION NEEDED\nIn my previous articles on this subject, I,\nexpressed the belief that we could obtain 80*\nper cent of the average annual wage earned\nby the worker through legislation and urged\nthat labor take steps to gain this legislation by\nunited action upon the national and state leg\nislative bodies.\nI am convinced that as long as unemploy\nment can at times be more profitable than\nemployment that there will continue to be\nperiods when mass unemployment will pre\nvail. This is the idea behind the guaranteed\nannual wage, for when workers receive 80\nper cent of their pay when unemployed, the\nneed for unemployment no longer exists since\na large share of purchasing power still re\nmains in the hands of the workers.\nI realize, of course, that there are those\nwho will claim that the guaranteed annual\nwage places a premium of shiftlessness and en\ncourages workers to prefer loafing to work\ning, but I can see how unemployment compen\nsation is handled and know that this would be\na very minor obstacle in the way of a guaran\nteed annual wage.\nNO HARDSHIP\nIt is not the wish of labor to work a hard\nship on employers, and such a guaranteed in\ncome would not be a hardship, for industry\nwould actually be priming the economic pump\nfrom which it derives the benefits of profits.\nNo doubt there would need to be some\ngovernmental aid which could come from\nsome type of fund paid for by the industries\nthemselves in somewhat the same manner that\nthe Federal Insurance Deposit Corporation in\nsurance works for banks.\nIf we can insure bank accounts up to\n$5,000, I can see no reason why we can\u2019t in\nsure jobs for the workers. As a matter of\nfact, unless we do guarantee income, bank de\nposits drop or completely dry up, credit stag\nnates and we enter a deflationary spiral that\nwe now know does not automatically end.\nGuaranteed annual \u2018wages for the work^r^\nis not visionary and impractical. It is bothC''\nnecessary and desirable if we are going to in\nsure a continuation of a healthy and progres\nsive economy. We can obtain this just as\nsurely as we have obtained our other gains, by\nlegislative action and in gaining another ad\nvance aid both labor and business to a more\nstable and healthier condition\nWashington\nLabor Report\nBy Bradford V. Carter\nSMALL PICKINGS\nJohn D. Small, administrator of the Civil\nian Production Administration is probably re\nsponsible for more goods lost to the economy^-^\nthan the loss caused by the strikes of the min-V?\ners, engineers and trainmen combined.\nIrrespective of the merits of the statistic^\nit comes with exceeding bad grace for Mr.\nSmall to charge that the mine strike had set\nback the production of important consumer\ndurable by three months.\nFrom the very start of his association with\nthe WPB, and later the CPA, Small has been\nthe spearhead of the campaign for the lifting\nof wartime controls. Along with his boss, J.\nA. Krug, then WPB chairman. Small worked\nand talked ceaselessly for the immediate re\nsumption of business-as-usual despite severe\nshortages in the civilian economy. Of a piece\nwith the rest of the Small ideas, it is worth\nnoting parenthetically his avdocacy, toward\nthe end of the war, of 9 civilian manpower\ndraft.\nKrug and Small turned a deaf ear to the\npleas of OPA that the maintenance of price\ncontrols would be impossible unless the WPB\nand the CPA maintained their controls. Bowles\nmade out an extremely effective case\u00bbthat un- v\nless the supply of materials were controlled\nit would be utterly impossible to maintain\nprice regulations and quality regulations.\nNATION PAYS\nThe nation is now paying the price for the\nIndecent haste with which Small and his busi\nness cronies in WPB demobilized production\nand allocation controls. We are paying for it\nin terms of the unavailability of low-cost\nhousing and clothing. And in the last analysis,\nmuch of the current turbulence may be at\ntributed to the unwillingness of the govern\nment to accept any responsibility for what\nhappened to the economy the day after war\nwas over.\nMr. Small was a central figure in the lift\ning of WPA controls over construction mate\nrials which made it possible for the specula\ntive high price builder to get materials ahead\nof the community which needed to build\nhomes for veterans. When the disastrous ef\nfects of this decontrolling became apparent\n(even to Mr. Small), he magnanimously de\ncided to give preference for building materials\nto houses selling for not more than $10,000.\nThat was a joke too because there were few\nveterans or workers who could afford to buy\na $10,000 hous\u00ab.\nNow, what I am getting at is this\u2014Small\nand his\u2019associates operated solely on the basiv\nof getting rid of controls not on the basis of\nthe kinds of controls necessary to maintain a\nhealthy economy during the transition from\nwar to peace. In doing this he worsened the\nprogress of reconversion regardless of whether\nit meant more profit-making for business al\nready overflowing with profits.","height":"26946","width":"19848"}}
